Figure~\ref{fig:latency-rate} shows latency as a function of injection rate for each traffic pattern.

\subsubsection{Uniform Traffic}

At low injection rates (0.01--0.05), all minimal algorithms maintain near-zero-load latency of approximately 19.5 cycles. GNNocRoute-PPO matches XY precisely, confirming that at low load, routing decisions have negligible impact on performance since there is no congestion to avoid. At rate 0.2, XY achieves 20.4 cycles and Adaptive XY/YX reaches 22.3. Planar Adaptive (119.8) and ROMM (134.0) show moderate increases, while GNNocRoute-PPO saturates at 521.7 cycles, indicating that the precomputed binary routing table creates path imbalance at this intermediate load level.

\subsubsection{Transpose Traffic}

Transpose traffic reveals distinct performance tiers. XY and Adaptive maintain 19.5--20.5 cycles up to rate 0.1, while GNNocRoute-PPO jumps to 44.0 cycles (115\% increase) due to suboptimal YX selections under diagonal traffic. Planar Adaptive (54.0) and ROMM (63.8 at rate 0.2) perform competitively with Valiant (58.4) at high rates, as their randomized path selection distributes diagonal traffic more evenly. At rates above 0.2, all algorithms saturate.

\subsubsection{Hotspot Traffic}

Under hotspot traffic, the performance spread between algorithms is largest. All algorithms remain near zero-load up to rate 0.02 ($\sim$20 cycles). At rate 0.05, adaptive algorithms shine: Planar Adaptive achieves 103.2 cycles, ROMM 125.4, and Minimal Adaptive 473.3. GNNocRoute-PPO (591.8) and XY (521.9) perform worst, suggesting that the GNN policy does not effectively redirect traffic away from the congested center. At rate 0.1, Planar Adaptive (176.3) and ROMM (219.7) maintain sub-300 cycle latency, while GNNocRoute-PPO (473.4) and XY (467.6) remain near saturation.

\subsection{GNN Encoder Analysis}

Despite the limitations of the current routing policy, the GNN encoder demonstrates strong topology learning capability. Figure~\ref{fig:gnn-analysis} shows the correlation between GNN node embeddings and betweenness centrality across topologies.

