\subsubsection{Hotspot Traffic Performance}

The most significant advantage of GNN-weighted routing appears under hotspot traffic. At injection rate 0.2, GNN-weighted achieves 314.3 cycles, a 16.9\% improvement over XY (378.0) and 12.0\% over Adaptive XY/YX (357.0). At rate 0.1, the improvement is 13.0\% over XY (254.4 vs.~292.4), and at rate 0.05, GNN-weighted achieves 342.9 cycles versus 374.2 for XY (8.4\% improvement). This demonstrates that the GNN-trained weight table effectively distributes traffic away from congested paths toward the hotspot node, outperforming both deterministic and locally-adaptive heuristics.

\subsubsection{Uniform and Transpose Traffic}

Under uniform traffic at low to moderate rates ($r \leq 0.05$), GNN-weighted maintains comparable latency (33.2--34.7 cycles) to XY (33.2--33.4) and Adaptive XY/YX (33.4--33.7). However, at rate 0.1, GNN-weighted latency increases sharply to 352.6 cycles with high variance (245--455 across seeds), indicating that the precomputed weight table creates path imbalance at this intermediate load level. Under transpose traffic, GNN-weighted also underperforms XY at moderate rates (370.9 vs. 33.8 at $r=0.05$), similar to the pattern observed with GNNocRoute-PPO on $4\times4$. These results suggest that the GNN-weighted approach requires further refinement for balanced traffic patterns at intermediate injection rates.

